for periodic chains of length L, where c is the central charge of the CFT. The constant term sq is non-universal but can be evaluated exactly in some cases [42], see Fig. 2(b). The ellipses in Eq. (2.3) represent subleading corrections to scaling, vanishing as power-laws of the subsystem size involving the Luttinger liquid exponent [44–48]. Open boundary conditions, discussed in more detail below (see Section 4.2.3), also leads to finite size corrections to the above logarithmic scaling [49,50]. Interestingly, power-law decaying corrections can be used to estimate the Luttinger exponent [51,52]. For exactly solvable one-dimensional models with multicritical conformal points described by unitary minimal models and Zn para-fermions, see also [53]. Finally, note that finite temperature corrections can also be computed using CFT [21,54,55].

2.1.2. Beyond bipartite entropy Despite the huge interest and the very large amount of works focused on bipartite entanglement entropies in one
dimension, let us also mention a few other many-body measures of entanglement.

2.1.2.1. Entanglement entropy of disjoint intervals. Several authors have considered how to estimate the amount of
entanglement between disjoint intervals using CFT [56–64]. In the case of two intervals A ∪ B = [x1A, x2A] ∪ [x1B, x2B],
as depicted in Fig. 3, CFT results lead to

